\begin{center}
    {\LARGE\textbf{Traffic Signal System}}\\[0.5cm]
    {\large Author: Albert Joy Mambrakaran}
\end{center}

\vspace{0.8cm}

\section*{Objective}

Design and simulate a fully functional traffic signal system using an Arduino Uno, LEDs, and appropriate resistors. The traffic signal operates in the following sequence:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Red signal active for 3 seconds
    \item Yellow signal active for 1 second
    \item Green signal active for 3 seconds
\end{itemize}

The sequence repeats continuously without interruption.

\section*{Circuit Connections}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
\hline
\textbf{LED} & \textbf{Arduino Pin} & \textbf{Resistor} \\
\hline
Red LED & D8 & 220 $\Omega$ \\
\hline
Yellow LED & D9 & 220 $\Omega$ \\
\hline
Green LED & D10 & 220 $\Omega$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\vspace{0.5cm}

The anode of each LED is connected to its respective Arduino digital pin through a 220 $\Omega$ resistor. All cathodes are connected to the common ground (GND) of the Arduino Uno.

\section*{Arduino Program}

\begin{lstlisting}[language=C++]
const int redLED = 13;
const int yellowLED = 12;
const int greenLED = 11;

void setup() {
  pinMode(redLED, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(yellowLED, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(greenLED, OUTPUT);
}

void loop() {

  // Red ON for 3 seconds
  digitalWrite(redLED, HIGH);
  digitalWrite(yellowLED, LOW);
  digitalWrite(greenLED, LOW);
  delay(3000);

  // Yellow ON for 1 second
  digitalWrite(redLED, LOW);
  digitalWrite(yellowLED, HIGH);
  digitalWrite(greenLED, LOW);
  delay(1000);

  // Green ON for 3 seconds
  digitalWrite(redLED, LOW);
  digitalWrite(yellowLED, LOW);
  digitalWrite(greenLED, HIGH);
  delay(3000);
}
\end{lstlisting}

\section*{Working Principle}

The Arduino controls three LEDs representing the red, yellow, and green traffic lights. The red LED remains ON for 3 seconds, followed by the yellow LED for 1 second, and then the green LED for 3 seconds. After completing the sequence, the program returns to the red signal and continues indefinitely, thereby simulating the operation of a basic traffic signal system.

\section*{Result}

The traffic signal system was successfully designed and simulated in Tinkercad. The LEDs operated according to the specified timing sequence and continuously repeated the traffic light cycle without interruption.

